text: I think the trailer doesn't quite do the movie justice--the movie is better than this.  It's nice that the whole movie isn't in the trailer, too, and there are jokes and plot points that you don't see so it's not a big give-away here.  The movie did a good job at referencing the familiar, classic jokes without relying on them to be the entirety of the movie.  I loved spotting the mini bundt cakes with flowers in the center in the Dancing Zorba restaurant, for instance, that were a quiet nod to the big bundt cake joke in the first movie.  Seeing this felt like getting together with old friends and I laughed out loud in parts.  Definitely loved it and would see it again in an instant!

text: Just saw it in theaters and was pleasantly surprise. Although not as good as the first one (for me) it was very nice to see the whole cast come back together for a nostalgic trip. You just have to sit down and watch it as a light hearted flick rather than the big blockbuster productions we've been getting. I will admit that there seemed to be a little more touchy feely scenes in here than the first one, which almost made it surpass the first for me (almost but not quite). Can still relate to the family too. It's not exactly Greek culture but more of an ethnic family culture in America. We're all guilty of it. Irish families, German, Italian, and for me my polish family. We're just proud of our heritage :). Overall I would say yes give this movie a go and don't overanalyze it. Just see it as an escape to remind you of some of the simpler things in life.

And funny enough just like the family in this, one of my parents isn't Greek, I have three cousins in each family but my own, we owned a restaurant, and my grandfather says to me to find a Greek girl. My life is basically this movie. And I love how much I can see the similarities.

text: I'm so glad to be a Canadian. Not a hyphenated Canadian like so many people in my country. My culture is Canadian, I speak English, I like hockey and butter tarts. My loyalty is to Canada, not some foreign country. I don't live in an enclave that speaks a different language, eats a different food, has a different religion. I'm Canadian like W.O. Mitchell, Margaret Lawrence, Stephen Leacock, etc. I cheer only for team Canada.
